  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering can result in significant criminal penalties, including:\n\n1. Potential prison sentences:\n- Up to 20 years in federal prison per offense\n- Maximum sentences can increase for more complex cases\n\n2. Financial penalties:\n- Substantial fines, often up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved\n- Potential forfeitures of assets related to the laundering activity\n\n3. Additional consequences:\n- Criminal record\n- Potential asset seizure\n- Potential loss of professional licenses\n- Potential immigration consequences for non-citizens\n\n4. Specific statutes involved:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 (Money laundering)\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1957 (Monetary transactions in criminally derived property)\n\nThe exact penalties depend on specific circumstances, including:\n- Amount of money involved\n- Source of laundered funds\n- Specific criminal intent\n- Prior criminal history\n\nSentencing can be complex and depends on detailed legal analysis of the specific case. Consulting with a qualified criminal defense attorney would provide the most accurate assessment for a particular situation.",
